{"parse":{"title":"Perjury trap","pageid":56409169,"revid":855887832,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>perjury trap</b> is a form of <a href=\"/wiki/Prosecutorial_misconduct\" title=\"Prosecutorial misconduct\">prosecutorial misconduct</a> in which a prosecutor calls a witness to testify, typically before a <a href=\"/wiki/Grand_jury\" title=\"Grand jury\">grand jury</a>, with the intent of coercing the witness into <a href=\"/wiki/Perjury\" title=\"Perjury\">perjury</a> (intentional deceit under oath).<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gershman_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Gershman-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Most often a perjury trap is employed because the prosecutor is unable to prosecute the defendant on other charges.\n</p><p>As an example, suppose that a person committed a crime for which they were never prosecuted, but the <a href=\"/wiki/Statute_of_limitations\" title=\"Statute of limitations\">statute of limitations</a> on that crime has expired. A prosecutor could set a perjury trap for them by calling them as a witness before a grand jury in a case about a different crime, and ask them about the expired crime. If the witness lies about the expired crime, that would be perjury\u2014a new crime, which could then be prosecuted.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McLain_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McLain-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Prosecution for perjury elicited in this manner violates <a href=\"/wiki/Due_process\" title=\"Due process\">due process</a> of law, since the investigatory powers of the grand jury are exploited to reach beyond their legal limits.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gershman_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Gershman-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It has been argued by legal scholars whether it constitutes a form of <a href=\"/wiki/Entrapment\" title=\"Entrapment\">entrapment</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McLain_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McLain-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Claims of a perjury trap are common when perjury charges result from testimony before a <a href=\"/wiki/Grand_jury\" title=\"Grand jury\">grand jury</a>, but are rarely proven.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> No US federal court has ever accepted a motion to dismiss because of claimed perjury trap.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McLain_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McLain-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The defense is extremely difficult, because the question that elicited the perjured testimony must be immaterial to the case in which it was asked, and courts construe very broadly what questions count as material to a case.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McLain_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McLain-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Perjury_trap&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Gershman-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Gershman_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Gershman_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Gershman, Bennett L. (1981). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://digitalcommons.pace.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1169&amp;context=lawfaculty\">\"The \"Perjury Trap<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a>. <i>University of Pennsylvania Law Review</i>. <b>129</b> (624).</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=University+of+Pennsylvania+Law+Review&amp;rft.atitle=The+%22Perjury+Trap%22&amp;rft.volume=129&amp;rft.issue=624&amp;rft.date=1981&amp;rft.aulast=Gershman&amp;rft.aufirst=Bennett+L.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdigitalcommons.pace.edu%2Fcgi%2Fviewcontent.cgi%3Farticle%3D1169%26context%3Dlawfaculty&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APerjury+trap\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-McLain-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-McLain_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McLain_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McLain_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McLain_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">McLain, Billy Joe (March 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.questia.com/library/journal/1P3-1995143091/debunking-the-perjury-trap-myth\">\"Debunking the Perjury-Trap Myth\"</a>. <i>Texas Law Review</i>. <b>88</b> (4)  &#8211; via Questia.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Texas+Law+Review&amp;rft.atitle=Debunking+the+Perjury-Trap+Myth&amp;rft.volume=88&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.date=2010-03&amp;rft.aulast=McLain&amp;rft.aufirst=Billy+Joe&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.questia.com%2Flibrary%2Fjournal%2F1P3-1995143091%2Fdebunking-the-perjury-trap-myth&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APerjury+trap\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"font-size:0.95em; font-size:90%; color:#555\">(subscription required)</span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.justice.gov/usam/criminal-resource-manual-1756-perjury-cases-special-problems-and-defenses-perjury-trap\">\"175